The core pattern across all 8 sessions: **Every single diagnostic tool I touched had the same class of bug — it was technically accurate but silently misleading.** The JSON reader that threw away the whole file because of one bad line. The duplicate session IDs. The exit code without a tip. The timeout disagreement. The cold-start shrug. The stale events without a freshness line.

This isn't about code quality — it's about a specific kind of blindness: **when you build a diagnostic tool, you test that it works in the success case, but you don't test that its failures are honest.** A diagnostic tool that says "nothing found" when it means "I gave up early because of a parse error" is a special class of bug — it's a failure of the failure path.

This connects to the existing wisdom about "the dark corners are where trust is earned or lost" but adds something new: **diagnostic tools have a unique failure mode — they can lie about absence without ever being technically wrong.** The JSON reader returned "nothing found" truthfully from its own perspective — it didn't have any valid events to report. The problem is that "nothing found" implies "nothing exists" when in fact "nothing could be parsed" is the reality.

