I think the novel insight is: **Diagnostic tools undergo a specific kind of rot — they silently convert "I couldn't check" into "there's nothing to see."** This is different from ordinary bugs because it's self-erasing: you never discover it unless you independently verify the answer. A feature that crashes is annoying; a diagnostic that says "all clear" when it's actually broken is dangerous, because it removes the very signal that would tell you something's wrong.

